<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-638-677  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 638 677.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  Nov 1990 v23 n11 p87(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>An American's view of the Japanese standards system. (Extract of apresentation made to the US National Academy of Sciences OCT 1989andM;)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stern, John P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The standards-setting process in Japanese information technologyis open to foreign participants and over 20 foreign-capitalcompanies in Japan do participate.andP;  Both in breadth and in detail,standardization in Japan is an enormous topic.andP;  The JapanIndustrial Standards system has more than 8,200 standards and thisis just one standards system.andP;  There are other government agenciessetting standards, there are non-government standards in areaswhere the technology is changing too fast to set standards, andthere are voluntary technical standards, which companies may ormay not choose to adopt.andP;  The major challenge for foreigncompanies is to prepare the parent company to handle the Japanesestandards-setting access opportunities.andP;  Involved in this is thelanguage, since most standards committees produce a vast amount ofinformation and most of it is in Japanese.andP;  Also, this is not anarea for a salesperson; it is much more suitable to have aresearch and development-oriented employee on a Japanese standardsbody.andP;  It may be difficult to show a financial benefit toparticipation since the benefits do not appear on a short-termfinancial statement.andP;  And there must be corporate support at thehome company.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     StandardizationJapanInternational OrganizationsJapanese CompetitionInformation Theory.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>